Perfect! The Thai spicy lemongrass soup was my absolute favorite. The veggie roll sushi comes a close second. Again perfect, and goes beautifully with the wasabi and ginger. Pad thai is my usual favorite but it comes in 3rd, not because it was anything less than great but because everything else was a smidge better. Also recommend the chiangmai curry lomain and the spicy salmon sushi rolls. Basically everything was perfect. The wait staff was perfect. The service was fast enough. We could ask for food to be made more or less spicy based on what we wanted. I couldn't expect anything better. If I had to nitpick I'd say that the ambience is good but not great. For the price, 100% worth it.

Since my fam and I go there often, the chef gives out a complimentary sushi roll EVERYTIME!!! The last time we went there, we were given free desserts! If you are looking for cheap noodles, look no further. This small shop has it all: noodle soups, stir fried noodles, sushi and fried rice (also other things). The bowl are HUGE so you get a lot of food for a pretty decent price averaging about $12 per bowl (sushi is a bit more expensive). The staff here are also amazing; I waited 8 whole minutes before my meal was right in front of me (honestly quickest service I've had in DC, I love it). There are plenty of vegetarian options (a little limited on the vegan options), but there is a lot of variety in the food, so plant based people won't be stuck with the usual eggplant Parmesan or other stereotypical vegetarian option. There is a four spice option that comes with the meal with an awesome selection to really customize your dish (use a small amount of the oil with the chili flakes in it and it will really jazz up your meal without overpowering your palette with spice... but only a small amount... seriously). Overall it was a very convenient restaurant for a Tuesday night dinner.

I was blatantly discriminated against at this restaurant because of the color of my skin. My wife and I are a black couple who ordered sushi here during lunch hour one day. The place was mostly empty when we entered except for one lady who had arrived before we got there. As we were taking our seats, another gentleman entered and took a seat. We were greeted by the waitress and ordered one spicy salmon roll and one spicy tuna roll. We regularly order sushi, so we are familiar with how long it usually takes for an order like this to come out. That being said, the lady was soon served her food which gave us no alarm. About twenty minutes later, the gentleman was served his food. Both of their orders were more elaborate than two sushi rolls. We hadn’t received any update on our order, so I asked the waitress about how much longer it would take. She said it was coming out soon. Around when the gentleman was served his food, two other patrons had sat down. Another twenty minutes pass, and these two patrons are now eating their respective orders. By this point, I had asked the waitress a couple more times on the status of the sushi rolls and she relayed the same message: it was coming out soon. I’ve ordered sushi dozens of times at restaurants and not once has an order with two sushi rolls taken close to an hour to prepare - especially during business lunch hours when other customers were receiving more labor intensive selections at a much quicker pace. Needless to say, we were the only black patrons there and got the point. What confirmed my suspicion of racial discrimination is that when we told the manager that we couldn’t stay longer because the request was taking too long and we had to get back to work, she offered no apology or explanation. She didn’t even address me. She simply shouted in another language toward the back and walked off. So we walked out and will never be back again.

I've been here three times and each time is amazing. I love how open the restaurant is. You can actually see them cooking in the back and the random flames are an added bonus. Nice place for lunch

I'm always wary of Asian fusion places, but this is hands-down one of the best spots in downtown DC. This hole-in-the-wall restaurant on the edge of Chinatown offers authentic noodle dishes from multiple Asian cuisines, as well as great sushi. Service is excellent and fast, and they're happy to accommodate dietary restrictions. They offer carryout and have a full bar. This is a great place for a quick bite, a date, or a group, and they have outside seating in the summer. Try the wasabi dumplings, Pad Thai, pho, and unique sushi rolls.
Great service, fantastic sushi

The mackerel sushi was quite good as is the service.

Rating solely based on their japchae. It's not primarily a Korean place so this might not be representative of the rest of their food, but the japchae tasted like cardboard and the veggies tasted freeze dried. Don't order japchae.

Best Asian dishes I've had in years. Wide range of choices and wonderful and friendly staff. The food was so good I ate their 10 lunches in a row and never got tired of the cuisine. Great lunch specials.

Each time we need to come into this part of DC (generally because of an event at the National Building Museum), we make a point of stopping here. I'm generally suspect of "pan" places that try to be all things to all people. (Think BBQ places that  sell TX, TN, KC and NC style. All of them are at best just OK)  Better in my experience to do one thing really well. Absolute Noodle is a happy exception. Whether you're getting dumplings, soup, noodles, rice bowls or sushi each will be good to exceptional, and when the VERY INEXPENSIVE price is factored in, it's a steal.
Food was delicious, but wasn't worth the 2.5 hour wait for delivery. The delivery driver said he would refund the order, but that never happened.
Great sushi and awesome soundtrack!
Fresh sushi with a great variety, very attentive service and quiet atmosphere. Great dinner spot!
Amazing place. Food is delicious, people are very nice and fast, and it's not expensive at all. Totally you have to go there !!!!

I have had a fair amount of sushi in my life and I have to say my experience here was definitely above average. I had the spicy crunchy asparagus roll and the spicy crunchy tuna roll with some curry soup here, and it was all delicious. The sushi was fresh and nicely presented, and I felt the prices were more than fair. The service was great and the food came out very quickly. I would definitely return here if I got the chance!

Our first time in DC and this restaurant, it's a hidden gem!! We highly recommend the Angel hair seafood noddle soup and the Bulgogi Udon, you won't be disappointed. The staff is very attentive and courteous, stop by for a bite.  Terry Georgia
Love the Noodles and Sushi. Nay is a nice owner/manager

We were very pleased with our meal here. The vegetable sushi was very good. The noodle dishes were excellent. Even our friend, who often has trouble due to food allergies was able to find something he liked. Large portions and extraordinary service. Vegan, gluten free, and soy free all readily provided. A low key, comfortable alternative to more pretentious venues around the area.

My husband had been home bound for 2 weeks since his surgery and literally tried every restaurant/food options in the area - we decided to give in to his noodle craving and gave Absolute Noodle a try  I stopped in to place an order to go - to my surprise, price was much more expensive compared to what was listed on their website. $15 dollars for a bowl of noodle with just one protein seemed a bit ridiculous especially the ones in such poor quality - overwhelmingly salty miso broth, undercooked udon, overcooked ramen, and dry, tough Bulgogi beef.  And since my brother in law really wanted sushi, we added the Godzilla roll - worst decision ever - it carried a strange foul, fishy aftertaste. We threw it out after half of a bite.  The service was extremely slow even though there was only one additional occupied table. 45 minutes just for two bowls of noodles and a roll of sushi? Furthermore, we felt ignored and forgotten in the corner after we placed and paid for our order.  Again, another Asian food fail in DC.

Nice decor and very friendly staff very reasonable prices with large portions. I really enjoyed the meal I had the Bangkokian Baby Back Ribs and like the previous reviewer said the ribs fell off the bone. The spring rolls was good as well

I tried to wean myself from the offer deals that are out there, but yesterday I was taking a group of teens into town for a staycation day. I needed a deal.  Absolute Noodle hooked us up with $40 for $20, so I checked it out. The bowls are huge, the food is fantastic and the service was spot on. You know what I appreciated the most? They didn't treat us any differently because we had the deal. Too many places put these things out there and then treat you like crap because you actually come in and use them.  The BBQ pork spare ribs fell off the bone. Delicious. We all tried different bowl combinations and all of them were great.  I'll definitely be back with the wife next time we're in the Chinatown area.
Solid lunch.  Quick service
